Introduction

South Korea, home to nearly 52 million people, has grappled with air pollution for decades. Despite the modest improvement in air quality over time, the issue continues to result in health problems, which increase healthcare costs, hurt worker productivity, and disrupt entire sectors of the economy. These pollutants originate both domestically, from fossil fuel combustion, and internationally, with a significant portion of fine dust pollution blowing in from China. The primary pollutant is PM2.5, a type of particulate matter less than 2.5 micrometers in diameter and often more hazardous to human health due to the ease with which it enters the lungs.

Given the economic and health impacts of poor air quality, it is essential to build more robust models that predict the PM2.5 levels of a given day based on recent and historical trends in temperature and precipitation. In other words, through understanding meterological data, South Korea can better anticipate periods of heightened pollutant activity, protecting sensitive populations the health risk of breathing unclean air while reducing the broader economic burden posed by pollution.

Our primary question is: to what extent do daily temperature and precipitation indicate daily and yearly trends in PM2.5 values across South Korea? To work up to this central question, we will first conduct EDA and later experiment with modeling. For regional insights, we will focus on three different areas:

  • Gwanak-gu, a district in Seoul (northwest, Seoul/Gyeonggi Province)
  • Hyeoksin-dong, a neighborhood in Jeonju (southwest, North Jeolla Province)
  • Cheongnim-dong, a neighborhood in Pohang (mid-east, North Gyeongsang Province)

This will allow us to understand geographical variations in our data.

Data Import and Cleaning

Dataset 1

Our first dataset, "South Korean Pollution," originates from Kaggle, uploaded by Caleb Reigada and originally obtained from https://www.airkorea.or.kr/web/. It contains the following variables:

  • date - date of measurement
  • pm25 - fine particulate matter (PM2.5) (g/m3)
  • pm10 - fine particulate matter (PM10) (g/m3)
  • o3 - Ozone (O3) (g/m3)
  • no2 - Nitrogen Dioxide (NO2) (ppm)
  • so2 - Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) (ppm)
  • co - Carbon Monoxide (CO) (ppm)
  • Lat - Latitude where measurement was taken
  • Long - Longitude where measurement was taken
  • City - City where measurement was taken
  • District - District where measurement was taken
  • Country - Country where measurement was taken

Dataset 2

Our second dataset comes from Open-Meteo's Weather API, with the following variables:

  • date - date and time
  • temperature_2m_mean - mean daily air temperature at 2m above ground
  • precipitation sum - sum of daily precipitation
  • location - location (gu = "district", dong = "neighborhood")

Three separate datasets will be imported, one for each location. Once the data is cleaned, we will combine all three datasets with Dataset 1.

In[12]:
cache_session = requests_cache.CachedSession('.cache', expire_after=-1)
retry_session = retry(cache_session, retries=5, backoff_factor=0.2)
openmeteo = openmeteo_requests.Client(session=retry_session)

locations = {
    "Gwanak-Gu": (37.48, 126.95),
    "Hyeoksin-Dong": (35.84, 127.06),
    "Cheongnim-Dong": (36.00, 129.41)
}

base_params = {
    "start_date": "2015-01-02",
    "end_date": "2022-01-01",
    "daily": ["temperature_2m_mean", "precipitation_sum"],
    "timezone": "Asia/Tokyo"
}

dfs = []

for name, (lat, lon) in locations.items():
    params = base_params.copy()
    params["latitude"] = lat
    params["longitude"] = lon

    responses = openmeteo.weather_api("https://archive-api.open-meteo.com/v1/archive", params=params)
    response = responses[0]  

    daily = response.Daily()
    daily_temperature_2m_mean = daily.Variables(0).ValuesAsNumpy()
    daily_precipitation_sum = daily.Variables(1).ValuesAsNumpy()

    daily_data = {
        "date": pd.date_range(
            start=pd.to_datetime(daily.Time(), unit="s", utc=True),
            end=pd.to_datetime(daily.TimeEnd(), unit="s", utc=True),
            freq=pd.Timedelta(seconds=daily.Interval()),
            inclusive="left"
        ),
        "temperature_2m_mean": daily_temperature_2m_mean,
        "precipitation_sum": daily_precipitation_sum,
        "location": name
    }

    df = pd.DataFrame(daily_data)
    dfs.append(df)

df2_gwanak = dfs[0]
df2_hyeoksin = dfs[1]
df2_cheongnim = dfs[2]

Joining Data

We'll next join our datasets, ensuring that the dates line up.

Data will be limited to 2015-2021. Also, we'll create copies of data that contains only readings from certain regions, in addition to a combined dataset.

In[18]:
df1_gwanak_filtered = df1.query("City == 'Gwanak-Gu' and date >= '2015-01-01' and date <= '2021-12-31'")
df_gwanak_joined = pd.merge(df1_gwanak_filtered, df2_gwanak, on='date', how='inner')

df1_hyeoksin_filtered = df1.query("City == 'Hyeoksin-Dong' and date >= '2015-01-01' and date <= '2021-12-31'")
df_hyeoksin_joined = pd.merge(df1_hyeoksin_filtered, df2_hyeoksin, on='date', how='inner')

df1_cheongnim_filtered = df1.query("City == 'Cheongnim-Dong' and date >= '2015-01-01' and date <= '2021-12-31'")
df_cheongnim_joined = pd.merge(df1_cheongnim_filtered, df2_cheongnim, on='date', how='inner')

All but one missing date occurs in our Gwanak dataset. The missing values may not affect EDA, but will hinder modeling. We can impute these values now:

In[35]:
df_complete_gwanak = df_complete_gwanak.set_index('date').reindex(date_range_g).reset_index()

In[36]:
df_complete_gwanak['month'] = df_complete_gwanak['date'].dt.month
df_complete_gwanak['day'] = df_complete_gwanak['date'].dt.day
numeric_cols = df_complete_gwanak.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns
df_complete_gwanak[numeric_cols] = df_complete_gwanak.groupby(['month', 'day'])[numeric_cols].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))
df_complete_gwanak[['Region', 'District']] = df_complete_gwanak[['Region', 'District']].ffill()

Over a seven year period, the temperatures across three regions of South Korea ranged from -16.2C to 31.6C (3F to 89F), with a mean of around 12.5C (54.5F). This suggests a fairly mild climate with possible cold snaps.

Precipitation varies more widely, from 0 inches to a whopping 110 inches in a single day. However, on average, 75% of days experience no more than 1.3 inches of precipitation, indicating that extreme rainfall in one day is not common. Our outlier values are likely linked to intense summer monsoons.

PM2.5 values have the greatest variation, ranging from 0 to 195 g/m3. The average PM2.5 level is 70.9 g/m3 with 75% of days recording levels of 88 g/m3 or less. This is considered "moderate," which may cause acute health problems in those with severe respiratory sensitivities. Whlie this may not sound severe, chronic exposure, compounded with "moderate" to "unhealthy" values of other pollutants like PM10 and NO2, can create long-term health issues in large groups of the population.

The variations in correlation coefficients between regions suggest that areas farther from China exhibit a stronger relationship between temperature, precipitation, and PM2.5 levels. With Gwanak-gu being the closest to China and Cheongnim-dong the farthest, there is a logical reason why our coefficients are stronger in regions farther from China. As previously suggested, temperature and precipitation are greater factors in determining air quality in these regions due to less pollution from China. Specifically, Cheongnim-dong, which receives the least fine dust from China, shows the strongest negative correlations. In contrast, Gwanak-gu, more exposed to external pollution sources, displays weaker correlations, suggesting that pollutants from overseas have a greater impact on air quality.

Our next step is to include a temporal aspect. We can incorporate a "lag" in our correlation statistics that assesses PM2.5 values against temperature and precipitation values from 1, 2, and 3 days earlier. This is necessary as the effect of temperature and precipitation on PM2.5 may not always take place within a day; for example, a certain temperature pattern on a Tuesday could have larger implications for Wednesday's air quality rather than the air quality of that same day.

Even with a lag implemented, our highest correlation between temperature and PM2.5 is only ~-0.44 (2-day lag). This suggests that temperature may have an impact on air quality two days later, but the difference between the 0-day and 2-day correlation is only 0.05 on average, and our sample size is only ~1000, so we cannot state this conclusively. On the other hand, precipitation appears to have an even weaker correlation with PM2.5 when a lag is included, suggesting it has a more rapid effect on PM2.5.

These trends hold across the three regions, with the temperature-PM2.5 correlation peaking at a 2-day lag. At the same time, the correlation between precipitation and PM2.5 either drops or remains roughly constant with increasing lag. This suggests that the effects of lag on climate and PM2.5 and are consistent across regions despite the relationship between climate and PM2.5 varying across regions.

Thus far, we've observed that the relationships between our three variables are not overwhelmingly strong when measured daily. Let's build a model to identify more subtle trends in our data.

Modeling

During the modeling phase, we'll use the Gwanak dataset, which spans from 2015 to 2021. However, we'll limit data to 2015-2019 to avoid the impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic on our models. While using the Cheongnim dataset might result in stronger models due to its slightly stronger relationships between climate and PM2.5, its data is limited to 2019-2021. Moreover, modeling the air quality in Gwanak, located in Seoul, home to nearly 10 million people, may hold more real-world relevance.

We'll work with XGBoost, a reliable and flexible modeling method that works via gradient boosting. It will take in temperature_2m_mean and precipitation_sum as features to model pm25. RMSE will be used as a model evaluation metric, and feature importance charts will indicate which features are of most value to the model. We'll also implement k-fold cross validation in order to use each year between 2015 and 2019 as the test set. This will ensure a more robust model, as 2019, or any year, could display unusual climate and PM2.5 patterns compared to surrounding years.

In[60]:
df_mod = df_complete_gwanak.query("date.dt.year <= 2019")

def cv_by_year(X, y, n_splits=4):
    time_split = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=4)
    rmse_list = []
    r2_list = []
    
    for train_i, test_i in time_split.split(X):
        X_train_cv, X_test_cv = X.iloc[train_i], X.iloc[test_i]
        y_train_cv, y_test_cv = y.iloc[train_i], y.iloc[test_i]
        model = xgb.XGBRegressor(n_estimators=300, learning_rate=0.03, max_depth=3, random_state=0)
        model.fit(X_train_cv, y_train_cv)
        y_pred_cv = model.predict(X_test_cv)
        rmse_list.append(root_mean_squared_error(y_test_cv, y_pred_cv))
        r2_list.append(r2_score(y_test_cv, y_pred_cv))
        
    return rmse_list, r2_list

train = df_mod.query('date.dt.year < 2019')
test = df_mod.query('date.dt.year == 2019')
X_train, y_train = train[['temperature_2m_mean', 'precipitation_sum']], train['pm25']
X_test, y_test = test[['temperature_2m_mean', 'precipitation_sum']], test['pm25']

rmse_list, r2_list = cv_by_year(X_train,y_train)

model = xgb.XGBRegressor(n_estimators=300, learning_rate=0.03, max_depth=3, random_state=0)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_preds = model.predict(X_test)

test_rmse = root_mean_squared_error(y_test, y_preds)
test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_preds)

rmse_list = rmse_list + [test_rmse]
r2_list = r2_list + [test_r2]
avg_rmse = sum(rmse_list) / len(rmse_list)
avg_r2 = sum(r2_list) / len(r2_list)

print("RMSE List (4-fold CV + test):", rmse_list)
print("Avg. RMSE:", avg_rmse)
print("R List (4-fold CV + test):", r2_list)
print("Avg. R:", avg_r2)

xgb.plot_importance(model)

Our base XGBoost model has an average RMSE of 31.47, meaning it predicts, on average, PM2.5 values 31.47 units away from the actual values in the test year. Moreover, the slightly negative R tells us that our model is performing a bit worse than a simple model that predicts the mean PM2.5. In short, this model is very weak. However, we can still extrapolate from the feature importance chart that temperature was utilized more by the model to make its predictions. This aligns with the higher correlation between temperature and PM2.5 (compared to precipitation and PM2.5) we observed earlier.

Let's now implement a lag and observe how our model improves. A lag allows us to incorporate past temperaure and precipitation values when predicting today's PM2.5 levels. This is worthwhile, as temperature from July 10th, for example, may not only affect July 10th, but also July 11th, July 12th, etc. We'll test all combinations of lag values between 1 and 5. This means well check how well the model performs when using just a 1-day lag, a 3-day and 5-day lag together, a 1-day, 2-day, and 4-day lag together, and so on.

(The values 1-5 were chosen based on intuition; higher values could be tested but this runs the risk of overfitting. And realistically, temperature and precipitation are unlikely to affect PM2.5 values 6 days out and onwards.)

In[62]:
lags = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

lag_combos = []
for i in range(1, len(lags) + 1):
    combos = itertools.combinations(lags, i)
    for x in combos:
        lag_combos.append(x)


res = []
for combo in lag_combos:
    df_tmp = df_mod.copy()
    for lag in combo:
        df_tmp[f'temp_lag_{lag}'] = df_tmp['temperature_2m_mean'].shift(lag)
        df_tmp[f'precip_lag_{lag}'] = df_tmp['precipitation_sum'].shift(lag)
    df_tmp = df_tmp.dropna()

    y_train = train['pm25']

    res.append({
         'lags': combo,

The optimal lag combination, with the lowest RMSE and highest R, is (1, 2, 3, 5), however the full lag combo (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5) has virtually the same performance. This indicates that incorporating 1-day, 2-day, 3-day, 4-day, and 5-day lags improved our model. While keeping the same machine learning algorithm and hyperparameters, incorporating a lag increased our R from -0.07 to 0.121. An R of 0.121 means that approximately 12.1% of the variability in PM2.5 values can be explained by same-day and lagged temperature and precipitation values together. Our model may be better than simply predicted the average PM2.5 value for every day, but our low R indicates that a lot of other factors shape each day's PM2.5 levels.

Additionally, our feature importance chart once again displays temperature being a more important feature than precipitation. It also rank 1-day lagged temperature as the feature with the most predictive power. This suggests that the temperature of the previous day is the most important temperature metric in predicting PM2.5. However, same-day temperature was least important of all temperature features, suggesting that same-day temperature is not as important after all. This finding may change as we develop our model and add more features.

Let's also investigate how lagged PM2.5 values themselves can be used. We'll now use previous values of temperature, precipitation, and PM2.5 itself to model PM2.5. In essence, we are trying to determine what additional value we add to our model when incorporating PM2.5 values as a feature.

Our R with only lagged PM2.5 as a feature is 0.322, close to our previous model's 0.425. This confirms that there is more predictive power in lagged PM2.5 as a feature than lagged temperature and precipitation, but that the latter features still add value to the model.

We are essentially left with two models:

  1. A model using only lagged temperature and precipitation (R = 0.121)
  2. A model incorporating lagged temperature, precipitation, and PM2.5 (R = 0.425)

Model 1 can be used to model PM2.5 long-term, but its very weak predictive strength prevents much practical use. However, it reveals a relationship between lagged temperature/precipitation and PM2.5, specifically that 1-day lagged temperature is the most significant predictors, aside from lagged PM2.5, and that temperature features, even with lags, are typically more indicative of PM2.5 values than precipitation features. (Basic correlation tests hinted at this, but not as conclusively.) Model 2 may have more practical use due to its stronger R, which indicates the supremacy of lagged PM2.5 as a predictor. However, because it requires PM2.5 values from earlier in the week, it can only be used for short-term forecasting, such as modeling the following day's PM2.5.

In reality, PM2.5 levels are influenced by many additional factors, such as wind speed, humidity, and atmospheric pressure. Incorporating these variables could further improve our models accuracy and allow it to generalize more efficiently. Further research could also investigate the relationship between our features and target variables across different regions in South Korea, as the eastern region of Cheongnim-dong was previously observed to have stronger relationships between climate and PM2.5 than the western Gwanak-gu.
